# Unity Editor Tooling Safety

- Keep tool scripts under `Assets/Game/Editor` editor-only; minimize dependencies on runtime assemblies.
- When an editor tool changes scenes or assets, add `Undo.RecordObject` or the appropriate Undo call so rollback works.
- After a tool changes objects, complete the `EditorUtility.SetDirty` flow and the required `PrefabUtility` flow when applicable.
- Bulk-edit tools must state their target filters clearly; do not default to touching the wrong scene or the whole project.
- Do not fail silently; log which asset/scene failed with `Debug.LogError`.
- Tool menu commands should be idempotent; running the same command twice must not corrupt data.

## Example

```csharp
// GOOD: Undo and dirty marking
Undo.RecordObject(targetComponent, "Update UI Binding");
targetComponent.RefreshBindings();
EditorUtility.SetDirty(targetComponent);
```
